00:40:56.796 --> 00:41:00.096 A:middle
to 100 percent complete
achievement, not part way.

00:41:00.676 --> 00:41:04.586 A:middle
And then, to get this
UI view controller

00:41:04.726 --> 00:41:06.596 A:middle
that represents the
composed sequence,

00:41:07.456 --> 00:41:08.786 A:middle
you're going to call a new API.

00:41:09.826 --> 00:41:13.716 A:middle
And it's available on both
GK achievement and GK score,

00:41:14.096 --> 00:41:15.196 A:middle
and it's this method here.

00:41:15.976 --> 00:41:18.486 A:middle
Its challenge composed
controller with players

00:41:18.666 --> 00:41:21.276 A:middle
where you can pass in an
optional list of friends

00:41:21.276 --> 00:41:23.466 A:middle
of the local player that
you wish to be preselected.

00:41:24.316 --> 00:41:26.956 A:middle
Then a message which is
an optional NS string

00:41:26.956 --> 00:41:29.796 A:middle
that you can pass that will pop
up in the composed controller

00:41:29.986 --> 00:41:32.066 A:middle
as the default message
that players can then edit.

00:41:32.066 --> 00:41:34.056 A:middle
And then the completion handler.

00:41:34.976 --> 00:41:36.796 A:middle
And when the completion
handler is called back,

00:41:36.886 --> 00:41:38.496 A:middle
that means that the
player happen

00:41:38.496 --> 00:41:40.356 A:middle
to either send the
challenge to their friends

00:41:40.886 --> 00:41:42.706 A:middle
or cancel sending the challenge.

00:41:43.026 --> 00:41:45.396 A:middle
And at this point, you need
to dismiss the view controller

00:41:45.396 --> 00:41:48.286 A:middle
and then do whatever
post processing you wish

00:41:48.496 --> 00:41:50.326 A:middle
because we also tell you
whether the player happened

00:41:50.326 --> 00:41:54.006 A:middle
to really issue that challenge,
and if they did, which friends

00:41:54.006 --> 00:41:55.946 A:middle
and player IDs they
sent that challenge to.

00:41:56.496 --> 00:41:59.586 A:middle
And then finally, once
you've gotten this incense

00:41:59.586 --> 00:42:02.246 A:middle
of the UI view controller,
you just need to present it

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:41:59.586 --> 00:42:02.246 A:middle
of the UI view controller,
you just need to present it

00:42:02.246 --> 00:42:04.806 A:middle
like you would any other UI
view controller within your app.

00:42:06.216 --> 00:42:07.156 A:middle
And that's it.

00:42:07.156 --> 00:42:08.776 A:middle
That's how you do
programmatic issuing

00:42:08.776 --> 00:42:11.036 A:middle
of challenges with iOS 7.

00:42:11.316 --> 00:42:14.386 A:middle
We think it makes it even
easier in order to allow players

00:42:14.386 --> 00:42:15.686 A:middle
to send challenges
to each other.

00:42:16.966 --> 00:42:19.346 A:middle
So you may be familiar already

00:42:19.606 --> 00:42:22.526 A:middle
with our existing
Issue Challenge

00:42:22.526 --> 00:42:23.656 A:middle
to Players Message method.

00:42:24.496 --> 00:42:26.646 A:middle
And since we've really
streamlined the way

00:42:27.016 --> 00:42:30.766 A:middle
that you can send challenges to
friends of your local player,

00:42:31.046 --> 00:42:32.816 A:middle
we're deciding to
deprecate this method.

00:42:33.516 --> 00:42:35.026 A:middle
And instead, we urge you to move

00:42:35.026 --> 00:42:37.196 A:middle
on to using the Challenge
Composed Controller

00:42:37.196 --> 00:42:41.236 A:middle
with Players Message
Completion Handler, the new API.

00:42:41.446 --> 00:42:45.116 A:middle
Now, in case your game is
running on an iOS 7 device

00:42:45.116 --> 00:42:48.826 A:middle
and is still using this legacy
API, they'll still work,

00:42:49.246 --> 00:42:51.696 A:middle
but we're going to present
a composed controller

00:42:51.696 --> 00:42:54.866 A:middle
and friend picker to the player
on your behalf automatically.

00:42:55.826 --> 00:42:58.386 A:middle
And this is great, but
I definitely urge you

00:42:58.386 --> 00:43:00.006 A:middle
to consider moving
over to the new API

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:42:58.386 --> 00:43:00.006 A:middle
to consider moving
over to the new API

00:43:00.216 --> 00:43:02.826 A:middle
because if you were
programmatically sending

00:43:02.826 --> 00:43:05.196 A:middle
challenges in the middle of
a gameplay session per se,

00:43:05.556 --> 00:43:08.096 A:middle
you definitely don't want
a view controller to pop

00:43:08.096 --> 00:43:11.516 A:middle
up in the middle of a player
jumping over a very wide pit.

00:43:11.696 --> 00:43:13.916 A:middle
So you know when
the timing is best

00:43:13.916 --> 00:43:15.066 A:middle
to actually present this UI.

00:43:15.796 --> 00:43:18.466 A:middle
So definitely move on to
the new API that we have.

00:43:20.356 --> 00:43:22.206 A:middle
So that's what's
new in Challenges.

00:43:22.436 --> 00:43:25.056 A:middle
We've got modal challenges
for selective completion

00:43:25.086 --> 00:43:27.106 A:middle
of challenges within
your game based

00:43:27.106 --> 00:43:28.506 A:middle
on context that you define.

00:43:29.426 --> 00:43:33.186 A:middle
We've got brand new programmatic
issuing of challenges API

00:43:33.276 --> 00:43:35.726 A:middle
to make it even easier to
send challenges to friends

00:43:35.756 --> 00:43:36.926 A:middle
with a local player
in your game.

00:43:37.996 --> 00:43:40.676 A:middle
And we've also-- because
of this streamlined API,

00:43:40.746 --> 00:43:42.826 A:middle
we've deprecated the
issue challenge API.

00:43:42.826 --> 00:43:46.036 A:middle
And if your game still happens
to use it when it's running

00:43:46.036 --> 00:43:49.566 A:middle
on iOS 7, it's still going
to work, but the new UI,

00:43:49.566 --> 00:43:51.776 A:middle
that new view controller,
is automatically going

00:43:51.776 --> 00:43:53.136 A:middle
to be presented to
the local player.

00:43:54.626 --> 00:43:57.176 A:middle
So that's Challenges,
that's what's new

00:43:57.276 --> 00:43:58.616 A:middle
in Game Center for Challenges.

00:43:58.616 --> 00:44:00.766 A:middle
Let's move on to the next
big topic of the day--

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:43:58.616 --> 00:44:00.766 A:middle
Let's move on to the next
big topic of the day--

00:44:01.276 --> 00:44:03.526 A:middle
handling events relevant
to the local player.

00:44:04.116 --> 00:44:07.006 A:middle
Now you may be familiar
with handling events

00:44:07.006 --> 00:44:09.806 A:middle
for the local player in the
Game Kit Framework today.

00:44:10.186 --> 00:44:12.856 A:middle
We have a lot of different
singleton objects that you had

00:44:12.856 --> 00:44:14.126 A:middle
to declare delegates for.

00:44:14.386 --> 00:44:18.146 A:middle
If you want to hook into when
the local player completed the

00:44:18.146 --> 00:44:20.136 A:middle
challenge, we have the GK
Challenge Event Handler

00:44:20.136 --> 00:44:23.216 A:middle
Singleton and we had the GK
Challenge Event Handler Delegate

00:44:23.266 --> 00:44:26.496 A:middle
Protocol that you would set as a
delegate for that event handler.

00:44:26.826 --> 00:44:28.526 A:middle
We also had things
for turn-based match--

00:44:28.676 --> 00:44:31.756 A:middle
or for a turn-based gameplay,
they had a singleton object,

00:44:31.806 --> 00:44:34.226 A:middle
and the GK Matchmaker
had an invite property.

00:44:35.176 --> 00:44:39.186 A:middle
Well, we've thoroughly revamped
the way and redefined the way

00:44:39.186 --> 00:44:42.266 A:middle
in iOS 7 that you can
handle events relevant

00:44:42.266 --> 00:44:43.146 A:middle
to the local player.

00:44:44.096 --> 00:44:45.486 A:middle
And we're doing it like this.

00:44:46.386 --> 00:44:49.786 A:middle
You can think of the GK Local
Player instance as the source

00:44:49.786 --> 00:44:52.516 A:middle
of all the events that are
relevant to your local player.

00:44:53.446 --> 00:44:55.966 A:middle
And so, whether the players
received the challenge,

00:44:55.966 --> 00:44:58.306 A:middle
completed the challenge,
gotten a new turn,

00:44:58.306 --> 00:45:01.046 A:middle
maybe a turn-based invite
or some matchmaking invite,

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:44:58.306 --> 00:45:01.046 A:middle
maybe a turn-based invite
or some matchmaking invite,

00:45:01.866 --> 00:45:03.706 A:middle
that's going to be channeled
through the local player.

00:45:03.706 --> 00:45:08.006 A:middle
And the local player can have
multiple listeners registered

00:45:08.036 --> 00:45:08.346 A:middle
to it.

00:45:09.296 --> 00:45:11.916 A:middle
And when a local player
listener is registered

00:45:11.916 --> 00:45:14.536 A:middle
on the local player and a
message happens to come in,

00:45:14.536 --> 00:45:17.866 A:middle
an event is triggered, that
listener or any listener

00:45:17.866 --> 00:45:21.926 A:middle
that is compatible for that
callback is going to get called.

00:45:22.086 --> 00:45:25.256 A:middle
Your listener object when you
register on a local player,

00:45:25.486 --> 00:45:28.626 A:middle
it needs to conform to the GK
Local Player Listener Protocol.

00:45:29.356 --> 00:45:33.796 A:middle
And this protocol, in turn,
conforms to three sub-protocols,

00:45:34.516 --> 00:45:36.156 A:middle
all defining optional methods.

00:45:36.156 --> 00:45:38.596 A:middle
None of the methods in these
protocols are required,

00:45:38.596 --> 00:45:39.686 A:middle
so you can pick and choose.

00:45:39.726 --> 00:45:42.536 A:middle
First is the GK Challenge
Listener Subprotocol

00:45:42.816 --> 00:45:44.656 A:middle
that defines the
various callbacks

00:45:44.656 --> 00:45:45.896 A:middle
that you can optionally conform

00:45:45.896 --> 00:45:49.116 A:middle
to when the player has completed
a challenge or had some sort

00:45:49.116 --> 00:45:51.156 A:middle
of challenge relevant
event occur.

00:45:51.836 --> 00:45:54.136 A:middle
We've also got GK
Turn-Based Event Listener

00:45:54.426 --> 00:45:56.616 A:middle
for turn-based gaming
specific callbacks

00:45:56.956 --> 00:46:00.476 A:middle
and GK Invite Event
Listener for GK Matchmaking,

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:45:56.956 --> 00:46:00.476 A:middle
and GK Invite Event
Listener for GK Matchmaking,

00:46:00.696 --> 00:46:02.426 A:middle
real-time matchmaking callbacks.

00:46:02.876 --> 00:46:06.646 A:middle
Once you've created your
listener, in order to register,

00:46:06.646 --> 00:46:07.836 A:middle
it's very straightforward.

00:46:08.596 --> 00:46:10.696 A:middle
I'm going to adopt one of
these subprotocols or any

00:46:10.696 --> 00:46:13.356 A:middle
of those methods and those
subprotocols, and you're going

00:46:13.356 --> 00:46:16.176 A:middle
to call on the Local Player
Instance Register Listener

00:46:16.436 --> 00:46:19.406 A:middle
passing this listener
instance that you've set up.

00:46:20.206 --> 00:46:23.456 A:middle
And you can pass-- you can
register multiple listeners.

00:46:24.636 --> 00:46:26.746 A:middle
And you also don't need
to worry about the timing

00:46:26.846 --> 00:46:28.396 A:middle
that you're registering
these listeners.

00:46:28.796 --> 00:46:31.706 A:middle
You may be familiar that
previously we asked you

00:46:31.706 --> 00:46:35.756 A:middle
to register or set delegates
on turn-based event handlers,

00:46:35.756 --> 00:46:37.886 A:middle
challenge event handlers,
all those other singletons

00:46:38.276 --> 00:46:40.596 A:middle
in the authentication
handler callback.

00:46:41.276 --> 00:46:43.176 A:middle
Well, you don't need to
worry about that anymore.

00:46:43.386 --> 00:46:46.616 A:middle
In case your-- the local player
happened to receive some sort

00:46:46.616 --> 00:46:49.536 A:middle
of event and there is
no listener registered

00:46:49.536 --> 00:46:51.636 A:middle
for the local player at
that time that could handle

00:46:51.636 --> 00:46:54.246 A:middle
that event, the local player
is going to cache that event.

00:46:54.916 --> 00:46:57.406 A:middle
So when you register
listener at some time later,

00:46:57.936 --> 00:47:01.156 A:middle
it'll have that event to
dispatch to your listener or all

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:46:57.936 --> 00:47:01.156 A:middle
it'll have that event to
dispatch to your listener or all

00:47:01.156 --> 00:47:06.326 A:middle
of the listeners that are
capable of handling that event.

00:47:06.456 --> 00:47:09.376 A:middle
So since we've talked a
bit about challenges today,

00:47:09.616 --> 00:47:11.186 A:middle
how about we take a look
at the group of methods

00:47:11.186 --> 00:47:13.776 A:middle
that you can implement
optionally within your listener

00:47:14.016 --> 00:47:16.386 A:middle
in order to hook into
challenge relevant gameplay?

00:47:17.676 --> 00:47:21.156 A:middle
The GK Challenge Listener
Subprotocol defines four

00:47:21.156 --> 00:47:25.086 A:middle
different methods that you can
optionally implement in order

00:47:25.086 --> 00:47:27.526 A:middle
to hook into challenge-specific
events concerning the

00:47:27.526 --> 00:47:28.186 A:middle
local player.

00:47:28.956 --> 00:47:31.556 A:middle
Let's take a quick look
through these different methods,

00:47:31.766 --> 00:47:33.846 A:middle
what they mean, and
how you can use them

00:47:34.046 --> 00:47:37.026 A:middle
within your listener
object or objects in order

00:47:37.096 --> 00:47:40.336 A:middle
to enable custom challenge
based gameplay in your game.

00:47:41.776 --> 00:47:44.926 A:middle
The first is concerning
selecting challenges.

00:47:44.996 --> 00:47:48.226 A:middle
That is, when a player
happens to receive a challenge

00:47:48.226 --> 00:47:50.696 A:middle
from a friend, whether
they are playing your game

00:47:50.696 --> 00:47:54.576 A:middle
or they're hanging around
in the Game Center app,

00:47:55.036 --> 00:47:58.876 A:middle
and they tap an iOS
notification center banner

00:47:59.086 --> 00:48:01.796 A:middle
or they tap a play bubble
within the Game Center app,

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:47:59.086 --> 00:48:01.796 A:middle
or they tap a play bubble
within the Game Center app,

00:48:02.446 --> 00:48:04.166 A:middle
or if they tap a play bubble

00:48:04.166 --> 00:48:06.036 A:middle
within the GK Game
Center view controller,

00:48:06.506 --> 00:48:09.456 A:middle
we're going to call back to
your listener Player Wants

00:48:09.456 --> 00:48:10.266 A:middle
to Play Challenge.

00:48:10.596 --> 00:48:12.146 A:middle
And really, what this means is

00:48:12.146 --> 00:48:14.956 A:middle
that the player tapped this
challenge banner and they want

00:48:14.956 --> 00:48:17.276 A:middle
to play your game in order
to complete that challenge.

00:48:17.666 --> 00:48:20.406 A:middle
So at that point, if you've
got challenge-specific gameplay

00:48:20.406 --> 00:48:24.356 A:middle
modes within your game, you
can call Self-Start Challenge

00:48:24.356 --> 00:48:26.086 A:middle
for Challenge if you've
got a method like that,

00:48:26.086 --> 00:48:27.646 A:middle
passing in the challenge to set

00:48:27.646 --> 00:48:29.816 A:middle
up this gameplay
mode for challenges.

00:48:31.176 --> 00:48:33.656 A:middle
Similar to selecting
challenges within your game,

00:48:33.656 --> 00:48:36.076 A:middle
we also got receiving
challenges.

00:48:36.646 --> 00:48:39.466 A:middle
This is an event that
is called back to your--

00:48:39.466 --> 00:48:40.966 A:middle
on your local player listener

00:48:41.606 --> 00:48:44.526 A:middle
when the player is playing your
game currently and they happen

00:48:44.526 --> 00:48:45.906 A:middle
to receive a challenge
from a friend.

00:48:46.596 --> 00:48:49.836 A:middle
At that time, player did receive
challenge is going to called

00:48:49.836 --> 00:48:53.356 A:middle
on your listener and you may
wish to present some custom UI,

00:48:53.356 --> 00:48:55.366 A:middle
like if Alice sent
Tom a challenge

00:48:55.366 --> 00:48:57.106 A:middle
to beat her track
score, you might want

00:48:57.106 --> 00:49:00.116 A:middle
to show Alice's picture right
there with the challenge message

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:48:57.106 --> 00:49:00.116 A:middle
to show Alice's picture right
there with the challenge message

00:49:00.116 --> 00:49:01.166 A:middle
that she happened to define.

00:49:01.546 --> 00:49:03.196 A:middle
And you could do that
within this method.

00:49:04.586 --> 00:49:08.066 A:middle
The last two methods in the GK
Challenge Listener Protocol are

00:49:08.066 --> 00:49:09.966 A:middle
concerning completing
challenges.

00:49:10.786 --> 00:49:13.516 A:middle
The first, when the local player
happened to complete a challenge

00:49:13.516 --> 00:49:15.806 A:middle
that they receive from a friend,

00:49:15.866 --> 00:49:18.826 A:middle
Player Did Complete Challenge
Issued by Friend is called

00:49:18.826 --> 00:49:20.966 A:middle
when the local player completes
a challenge in your game.

00:49:21.596 --> 00:49:24.026 A:middle
And at this point, you know,
if you want to congra--

00:49:24.026 --> 00:49:26.356 A:middle
display a congrats banner to
the player or whatever UI,

00:49:26.826 --> 00:49:29.366 A:middle
maybe even reward them
gameplay-wise within your game,

00:49:29.516 --> 00:49:30.356 A:middle
you could do that here.

00:49:30.856 --> 00:49:35.606 A:middle
And then, also, when the
local player's friend happened

00:49:35.606 --> 00:49:38.676 A:middle
to have completed the challenge
that the local player sent then,

00:49:39.506 --> 00:49:43.146 A:middle
that's where Player Issue
Challenge was Completed

00:49:43.316 --> 00:49:45.656 A:middle
by Friend is going to be
called back on your listener.

00:49:46.406 --> 00:49:48.246 A:middle
At this point, you might
want to inform the player

00:49:48.246 --> 00:49:49.856 A:middle
that perhaps their friends
are a little bit better

00:49:49.856 --> 00:49:53.126 A:middle
than they thought they were,
and again, do whatever you wish

00:49:53.126 --> 00:49:55.466 A:middle
in your game that makes sense.

00:49:56.136 --> 00:49:58.566 A:middle
So that's just how
challenges work

00:49:58.566 --> 00:49:59.956 A:middle
with GK Local Player Listener.

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:50:00.696 --> 00:50:02.546 A:middle
But we're also doing a lot

00:50:02.546 --> 00:50:05.046 A:middle
of things concerning
turn-based gaming as well

00:50:05.046 --> 00:50:06.706 A:middle
as real-time matchmaking.

00:50:07.186 --> 00:50:09.926 A:middle
Those are all built with
the GK Local Player Listener

00:50:10.576 --> 00:50:11.946 A:middle
architecture as well.

00:50:12.796 --> 00:50:15.726 A:middle
And as you may guess, that
means that we are, in turn,

00:50:15.956 --> 00:50:18.276 A:middle
deprecating the GK
Challenge Event Handler,

00:50:18.916 --> 00:50:22.136 A:middle
the GK Turn-Based Event Handler
Singleton and their delegates,

00:50:22.136 --> 00:50:24.206 A:middle
as well as the Invite
Handler property

00:50:24.466 --> 00:50:26.646 A:middle
of the GK Matchmaker object.

00:50:27.806 --> 00:50:30.886 A:middle
And since this affects
multiplayer as well, tomorrow,

00:50:30.886 --> 00:50:33.416 A:middle
Nathan's got a multiplayer
session,

00:50:33.526 --> 00:50:35.836 A:middle
making multiplayer
games with Game Center,

00:50:35.836 --> 00:50:37.876 A:middle
I definitely urge you to
check that out in order

00:50:37.876 --> 00:50:41.196 A:middle
to learn how you can adopt GK
Local Player Listener Protocols,

00:50:41.486 --> 00:50:43.596 A:middle
in order to use turn-based
gaming

00:50:43.596 --> 00:50:45.546 A:middle
within your game
and GK Matchmaking.

00:50:47.616 --> 00:50:51.366 A:middle
So we've learned a lot of
different things today.

00:50:51.486 --> 00:50:54.476 A:middle
In addition to our brand new
UI that we've also got going

00:50:54.476 --> 00:50:56.446 A:middle
on with the GK Game
Center view controller,

00:50:56.846 --> 00:50:59.066 A:middle
we've increased the maximum
amount of leaderboards

00:50:59.066 --> 00:51:02.046 A:middle
that you can use within your
game to 500 leaderboards.

WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00.000

00:50:59.066 --> 00:51:02.046 A:middle
that you can use within your
game to 500 leaderboards.

00:51:02.466 --> 00:51:04.446 A:middle
And you can impose a
hierarchical structure

00:51:04.446 --> 00:51:07.696 A:middle
on these leaderboards with a new
feature called Leaderboard Sets.

00:51:08.426 --> 00:51:10.726 A:middle
Most Recent Score Leaderboards,
in case you want to make it

00:51:10.726 --> 00:51:14.006 A:middle
such that player scores on
a leaderboard can go both up

00:51:14.006 --> 00:51:17.556 A:middle
and down, and completely
